<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / Arts: Sopranos fall flat - Off the Wall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Three Tenors are having a return match. They are getting together in
Pasadena just before the start of the World Cup in June hoping to repeat the
success of their last venture into popular culture, which took them spinning
up the pop charts. The incentive is a Dollars 12m fee.
But while Pavarotti, Domingo and Carreras are all reasonable men, prepared
to drown their rivalries in return for money in the bank, no such good
fortune followed an attempt to cash in with The Three Sopranos. Kiri Te
Kanawa, Jessye Norman and Kathleen Battle were invited to get together in
Vienna on another money making spree. The ladies could not even agree on
their frocks and the idea was quickly abandoned.
It is hard to mention international singers without referring to money.
Domingo has been approached to star in the movie version of Phantom of the
Opera, a booking which could be worth around Dollars 20m. He is very keen,
but wants to test himself in the role first. So plans are afoot to give him
a week's trial in the stage version. Its quite possible that anyone with a
ticket for Phantom at the Haymarket in the next few months could be sharing
the experience with a cuddly Spanish tenor.
This week Covent Garden made its pitch for millennium money. In the dear,
dead, old days of the late 1980s it hoped to finance the badly needed
renovation of the Opera House by renting out offices and shops on the site.
It has now re-launched the scheme, substituting as fairy godmother, the
Millennium Fund for offices. The cost now will be around Pounds 100m.
The Millennium Fund will be one of the five beneficiaries of the Lottery
when it comes on stream next year. No one knows how much people will bet: if
they are cautious then around Pounds 70m a year will be available for
Millennium projects; if they love the idea it could be Pounds 200m. If the
higher target is reached then Covent Garden stands a good chance of scooping
some of the cash set aside for London.
The Lottery Commissioners have made it clear they will spread the largesse
around the country, and the London tranche is already being fought over by
the new Tate Gallery of Modern Art; a smartened up South Bank; an
Albertropolis of museums in Kensington; and a theme park in Greenwich.
By getting its bid in early Covent Garden hopes for the best. It should know
by early next year whether it has been chosen as a millennium project. It
will then launch its public appeal. The ideal financial break down for the
project would be around Pounds 15m from commercial rents; Pounds 35m from
the Lottery; and the remaining Pounds 50m from rich and loyal friends like
Lord Sainsbury, Lord Rothschild, and Mrs Vivien Duffield.
If all goes well Covent Garden will close for rebuilding in the autumn of
1997; move temporarily to the Theatre Royal Drury Lane; and return to the
Royal Opera House by the autumn of 2000 in time for the millennial
celebrations.
When asked to name his achievements at the Arts Council, out-going boss
Anthony Everitt boldly plumped for Arts 2000. This was Lord Palumbo's wheeze
under which a different city or region hosted a different art form each year
up to the millennium.
It has proved a hit and miss affair, getting off to a good start with
Birmingham City of Music in 1992; faltering with East Midlands Region of
Dance last year; and certainly helping Manchester City of Drama 1994 to keep
open theatres which had been faced with closure because of capping. Swansea
City of Literature in 1995 has had terrible management problems but now the
council has stepped in to avoid humiliation; and Northern Region is hosting
the Visual Arts in 1996.
This week, rather surprisingly, East of England beat off bids by Devon &amp;
Cornwall and Leeds to become the region of Opera and Musical Theatre in
1997. It is getting Pounds 500,000 from the Council, the largest grant to
date, to make good its ambitious policy of new commissions.
</TEXT>
