<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / FT Guide to Personal Equity Plans - Combined Bond-and-Equity
PEPs (15): A tax cherry in a portfolio cocktail - The savings industry
lobbied the chancellor for a Pep-like allowance for gilts or gilt funds, but
he did not oblige. Bethan Hutton examines the possible compromises available
to investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The ideal portfolio for the typical private investor is usually said to
consist of a mixture of shares, fixed-interest securities and cash on
deposit. The proportions should vary according to your stage of life,
attitude to risk, view of the market, particular need for income or capital
growth, and so on.
So if a Pep is to be a central part of your portfolio, it would seem logical
for it to furnish more than one of these elements. However, the government
has other ideas. Personal equity plans, as their name suggests, are intended
to encourage equity investment, not to act as tax shelters for lower-risk
investments such as gilts or cash.
The savings industry lobbied the chancellor before the last Budget for a
Pep-like allowance for gilts or gilt funds, but the chancellor did not
oblige, and is unlikely to in the foreseeable future. The government's
priority now is to get people spending again, rather than encourage them to
save more.
Although a Pep cannot be used to invest solely in gilts or bonds, you can
get some exposure to them in combination with ordinary shareholdings.
However, two investment management groups (Foreign &amp; Colonial and Save &amp;
Prosper) ran into trouble last year, when the Inland Revenue decided that
funds they were marketing for inclusion in Peps were not eligible for Pep
investment, as less than 50 per cent of their assets were in the form of
shares.
The Revenue deemed that such funds could not be held in a Pep, even up to
the Pounds 1,500 limit for investment in 'non-qualifying' funds. Only funds
which were less than 50 per cent invested in bonds or gilts were 'pepable'.
The government's ruling has created the anomaly that a single fund can
invest up to 49 per cent in bonds or gilts and still qualify for Pep
investment; but an investor putting together a self-select Pep cannot
include any gilts, bonds or funds which are more than half invested in bonds
or gilts, even if the total holding of fixed interest securities within the
Pep is less than the regulation 50 per cent.
Curiously, although the Revenue has clamped down on using Peps to invest in
fixed-interest securities, it has not done the same for holdings of cash. At
the moment, there is no fixed limit on how much of your Pep can be held in
cash, or for how long, before you use the money to buy shares or units in a
trust. This is perhaps because cash is not an enticing prospect for
investors at the moment, due to low interest rates.
Shortly after the Revenue ruling on bonds, a number of other investment
management groups came up with pepable unit trusts designed to exploit the
50 per cent limit. The idea of a Pep which can combine bond/gilt and equity
investment is appealing to many investors, because it will tend to produce
more income than most funds invested solely in equities. For most people, at
least in the first few years, the main attraction of a Pep is the income tax
exemption, not the capital gains tax one, as relatively few people pay
capital gains tax.
There are four funds designed for Pep investment which fall into this
category: Cazenove Utility &amp; Bond fund, Fidelity High Income, Guinness
Flight Equity &amp; Bond Income, and M&amp;G Managed Income Fund.
The M&amp;G Managed Income fund, which puts together a selection of M&amp;G unit
trusts, including gilt funds, gets around the rule because it is a
fund-of-funds, structured as a unit trust in itself, rather than a Pep
wrapper around a mix of individual funds.
The other three trusts fall into the category of UK balanced funds - ie
those which hold a mixture of shares and bonds or gilts. Their main emphasis
is on income, but they do also offer the prospect of some capital growth.
They tend to invest in higher-yielding shares, such as utilities. Not all
balanced funds are suitable for Pep investment, as their holding of bonds
may slip over to more than 50 per cent.
Chris Burvill, manager of Guinness Flight's Equity and Bond trust, says: 'We
designed it very much as a Pep product. It is meant to be a low-risk fund.'
He sees the fund's advantage as offering a high yield, through investing in
high-yielding stocks and corporate bonds, but also presenting a lower risk
than a pure equity fund. At the moment, the fund has about 65 per cent
equities, and 35 per cent corporate sterling Eurobonds. The equity portion
was higher and is gradually being reduced.
The lower risk level of balanced funds is partly due to their defensive
capacity. Managers are able to increase the fund's weighting in equities
when the stock market looks set for a good run, then lock in growth by
switching back to more stable bonds when they feel shares are becoming
over-valued. This tends to mean, however, that capital growth is slower than
that of more equity-oriented funds.
Performance of the Guinness Flight fund was above average for the UK
balanced funds sector over the six months to February 1, ranking 16 out of
42 funds (source: Micropal). 'We are competing against funds which have up
to 80 per cent in equities, so if we can be half-way up in a very strong
bull run in the market, we should do quite well on the down side,' Burvill
says.
Cazenove's utility and bond fund did even better, ranking second overall in
the same sector, while Fidelity was at number 31. M&amp;G's Managed Income trust
was 17th out of 60 funds in the fund-of-funds sector.
John Spiers, of Best Investment, warns that some of these Peps have high
management charges, which he says are hard to justify. 'If you do want to be
conservative and go for this sort of fund, management charges are more
important than they would be for an equity fund,' he says.
For example, M&amp;G has an annual management charge of 1.5 per cent; Guinness
Flight's annual charge for the Pep is 1.25 per cent; Fidelity also charges
1.25 per cent; while Cazenove charges 0.5 per cent on the underlying unit
trust, and Pounds 30 plus VAT for the Pep from the second year onwards.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6733 Trusts, NEC.
    P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
