<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / FT Guide to Personal Equity Plans - Single-Company PEPs
(13): Not for the first-timer - Availability is different from suitability,
observes Alison Smith. The tax benefit may not always be worth the
additional risk for the small investor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Is it worth putting all your eggs in one basket, even if the chancellor
encourages you to do so?
The chancellor's encouragement might in itself be enough to deter many
people from any course of action, but in terms of the Inland Revenue,
single-company Peps are a free gift, an added bonus.
Apart from the general Pep tax allowance of Pounds 6,000, there is a special
allowance of Pounds 3,000 plus charges if you invest in a Pep made up
entirely of one company's shares.
The idea was introduced by Norman Lamont in his 1991 budget, as another move
in the government's campaign to create a nation of share-owners. They were
devised primarily for employees who received shares through a share option
scheme - giving them a perpetual tax shelter - but are available to anyone
who chooses to take one out.
Availability is different from suitability, however. There is a real
question whether the extra tax benefit is worth the additional risk for the
small investor of choosing just one company.
Chase de Vere, the independent financial adviser which publishes an annual
Pep guide, is not alone in believing that normally it is worth considering a
single company Pep only if the general Pep tax allowance has been fully
used.
The process of taking out a single-company Pep can also involve more stages
 -and more decisions - than might be expected.
Someone working in a company and moving from an Inland Revenue-approved,
all-employee share scheme can move their shares straight into an SCP,
provided that this is done within 90 days of the shares emerging from the
scheme.
Qualifying new share issues, which are generally available, also allow any
investor to transfer straight into a single-company Pep, as for a general
Pep, provided they do so within 42 days of the allotment letter.
But in all other cases, the procedure of turning one company's shares
already held into an SCP is more complicated. The nearest equivalent is to
sell an existing holding, put the proceeds into an SCP, and tell the
investment manager to buy the same amount of of the same stock.
Even this approach could leave the investor vulnerable to capital gains tax
on the sale of the shares, as well as giving rise to dealing costs.
Then there is the question of which type of SCP to choose, as well as which
company. There are two broad varieties: those which are solely for one
company; and those where either the investor or the investment manager
decide which company to put the money into.
Not all Pep plan providers offer all kinds of SCPs. Bradford &amp; Bingley
building society, one of the leading independent Pep providers, for example,
offers over 60 different single-company Peps, but for each of them just one
company is specified, and there is no discretionary ability to switch.
Then there is the question of charges.
Many company schemes are cheaper than taking out an SCP through an
independent Pep plan manager, though extra charges would be incurred by
investors deciding after all that they did not want to hold a particular
stock forever, and wanted to change to another company.
Bradford &amp; Bingley has uniform fees for its single-company Peps. The initial
charge is Pounds 15 plus value added tax, though in some cases this is paid
by the company. Its annual charges are 0.5 per cent plus VAT, in some cases
with a minimum of Pounds 5, and it makes no charge for early encashment.
Though not quite the cheapest, at 0.25 per cent, its dealing charge is at
the low end of the scale.
Most independent Pep plan managers offering an SCP have front-end charges in
the 0.5-1.5 per cent range, with an annual charge of 0.75-1.5 per cent
thereafter. Dealing charges can rise to around 1.90 per cent.
Single-company Peps where the fund manager chooses which stock to invest in
can tend to be cheaper than those where the final decision is left to the
investor, whatever the manager may advise.
In the end, however, provided that the investment is in a stock where the
yield is high enough to cover the charges, the decision whether to take out
an SCP rests on broader issues than differences in percentage points on
fees.
'SCPs are not for somebody who has decided to venture into the stock market
this year for the first time and take out Pounds 6,000 in a general Pep and
Pounds 3,000 in a single-company Pep,' says Brian Tora, of stockbrokers
Greig Middleton. 'That amounts to putting one-third of your investment in a
single company, which many investment managers say would be a high-risk
strategy.'
Robin Bloor, of Chase de Vere, takes a similar view. 'If you would not
normally put Pounds 3,000 into a single company, there's no point in doing
it just to be tax-free,' he says.
Many investment managers would advise an investor not to have more than 10
per cent of a portfolio in any one company, suggesting that someone with
investments of under Pounds 30,000 should perhaps be cautious about taking
out an SCP.
Others would put the case even more strongly, arguing that the real
advantage of SCPs lies in the shelter from capital gains tax, perhaps
implying a portfolio of Pounds 50,000 or more.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
