<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / FT Guide to Personal Equity Plans - Personal Financial
Planning (11): A friend for life, and those days when you need a little
extra - The tax-break offers a means to repay a mortgage or meet school
fees, yet it is little used in such areas. Eric Short considers the
possibilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Peps should form the core holding in the portfolios of investors who are
interested in the UK equity market.
Yet, while much is written about their tax-efficiency and flexibility, and
though the Pep market is constantly monitored for performance and charges,
less attention is given to the role that Peps should play in an individual's
financial planning strategy.
When someone has decided to invest in equities, whether directly into shares
or indirectly through collective funds, the bedrock of that investment
should be Peps. However, there are certain specific investment requirements
where a Pep should also be considered.
Many people who are in an employer's pension scheme want to boost their
retirement income beyond that provided by the scheme. In these days of
labour mobility, few will qualify for anything approaching the maximum
pension.
The traditional means of boosting a company pension is through additional
voluntary contributions (AVCs). But, although AVCs are highly tax-efficient
in accumulating cash, with tax relief on the contributions and investment in
gross funds, the benefits must be taken at the time of retirement as taxable
income. If the AVCs have been invested in equities and there is a bear
market at the time of retirement, the individual could suffer through being
forced to cash in the contract and buy a pension annuity.
In contrast, although contributions to a Pep are paid out of taxed income,
investment is tax-free (as with AVCs), and the benefits are both flexible
and tax-efficient. The benefits can be taken at any time. The investor may
take the dividend or distribution tax-free to boost income, leaving the
underlying capital intact.
Alternatively, he can use some or all of the accumulated capital to buy an
ordinary annuity - only part of that annuity's payments being taxable, in
contrast to a pension annuity where all the payment is taxable. If the
equity market is low, the investor can wait until it recovers before cashing
in.
It is not easy to make direct comparisons of the benefits provided by AVCs
and Peps. Ultimately it is a matter of personal preference. But the nearer
the investor is to retirement when he decides to invest in order to boost
his future income, the more advantageous is a Pep.
He is free to make his own arrangements for saving through a Pep, in
contrast to AVCs where the pension administrator would handle the
arrangements for investment in the in-house AVC - though not in the case of
a free-standing AVC from a life company. But, of course, the investor can
save through both AVCs and Peps, if he can afford it.
Most people in company pension schemes take the tax-free cash sum that is
available to them at retirement, in return for a lower pension - an exercise
known as 'commutation'. But most of these have only a hazy idea of what to
do with the cash when they receive it.
After paying for a Caribbean cruise, some of the remaining cash could be
invested in a Pep, which can be used to boost income, or to build up a cash
sum for use in later years or to be passed on to the next generation.
Another important specific requirement of many individuals is repayment of a
mortgage. When Peps were first launched, Pep mortgages were the vogue.
Financial advisers and journalists were strong advocates of their use as a
way to build up the sum necessary to repay a loan. The tax-free accumulation
of funds and the tax-free cash-in at the end looked highly attractive, until
the 1990 bear market reminded investors that equity prices could go down as
well as up.
Now, little is heard of Pep mortgages, which is a pity, because, properly
used, they are more tax-efficient than endowment or repayment mortgages.
Equities have, over the long-term, outperformed fixed-interest investments;
and mortgages are long-term commitments.
True, if the investor holds the Pep until the mortgage is due for repayment,
he runs the risk of having to cash in during a bear market; but if he adopts
the strategy of gradually switching out of the Pep and into deposits ahead
of the repayment date, he will avoid that risk, though at the expense of tax
efficiency.
A third specific investment requirement, for couples who want their children
educated in the private sector, is to save in advance saving towards payment
of school fees, which rise at least as fast as, if not faster than,
inflation. Savings towards these fees might be invested in assets, such as
equities, where the returns match inflation over the long term.
Peps should form part of such savings, though care is needed. The time until
fees will be due is comparatively short - 10 years if the individual is
planning well in advance, but often much less. However, since the fees are
payable over a five-year period, there is room for flexibility in cashing in
the Peps. Nevertheless, there should also be other savings, to cover parents
against the consequences of being forced to cash in Peps in a bear market.
</TEXT>
