<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / FT Guide to Personal Equity Plans - Investment Trusts (5):
Keep an eye on the assets - Trust companies have been tackling the problem
of discounts in a number of ways, writes Bethan Hutton, including monthly
savings schemes to provide a steady demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investment trusts have been around for more than a century, but the past few
years have seen a spectacular revival in their fortunes. At least part of
this has to be due to the popularity of investment trust Peps, particularly
since the tax-break was widened to allow the full Pounds 6,000 to be
invested in collective funds.
Like unit trusts, investment trusts offer investors, even those with very
modest savings, exposure to a wide spread of shares, thus reducing the risk.
There are fewer investment trusts than unit trusts, but they offer a huge
variety, from general UK and international funds to specialist funds
investing in a single country or using a particular strategy.
Many of the longest-established investment trusts, such as Foreign &amp;
Colonial's flagship fund, are general international funds which have been
reluctant to become fully qualifying for Pep investment, as this would mean
guaranteeing that at least 50 per cent of their holdings would be in the UK
or the rest of the European Union. However, many of the same investment
management groups have set up newer trusts which are fully Pep-qualifying,
using the same investment expertise, but focused on a narrower area.
Of course, you can still invest up to Pounds 1,500 a year in non-qualifying
funds, and the investment trust sector offers a wide choice of these.
Investment trusts have fewer investment restrictions than unit trusts; so,
for example, emerging market investment trusts can be more genuinely
adventurous than their unit trust counterparts, which can only put 10 per
cent of the fund into 'unapproved' stock markets. Investment trusts can also
offer some innovative structures, such as split-capital trusts (see facing
page).
One important difference between unit and investment trusts is that the
price of shares in investment trusts fluctuates according to market demand,
unlike the price of units in unit trusts, which is set by the trust's
manager, and relates directly to the value of the underlying assets. This
can mean that if shares in an investment trust are in demand, you pay a
higher share price than its underlying assets are worth. When this happens,
the share is said to be trading at a premium. More usually, investment trust
shares trade at a discount - the value of the assets per share is higher
than the price of the share. At the moment, discounts are at historically
narrow levels.
If you buy shares at a premium or a narrow discount, you run the risk that,
even if the trust's portfolio performs well, if the trust itself ceases to
be so popular, the share price could slip back to a wider discount by the
time you want to sell. A considerable part of investment trusts'
outperformance of unit trusts over the past few years can be attributed to
the narrowing of discounts, but a widening would lead to underperformance.
Investment trust companies have been tackling the problem of discounts in a
number of ways, including setting up monthly savings schemes to provide a
steady demand.
Savings schemes are popular with many small investors who are worried by the
ups and downs of the stockmarket. By investing a fixed amount - say Pounds
50 - every month, you buy more shares when the price is low, and fewer when
the price is high. This lowers the average cost of the shares you buy, and
reduces the likelihood of your putting in a lump sum at the top of the
market and seeing your investment take a dive the next week. You can also
contribute to a Pep through a savings scheme.
Many, but not all, investment trust management groups run their own Peps.
The alternative is to take out a self-select Pep with an independent
manager, and use it to buy investment trust shares. The choice between these
two approaches depends on the charges, but also how wide a choice of funds
you want to be able to include in your Pep.
Some investment trust groups only include two or three trusts in their Peps,
whereas others give you free choice of all their funds, and sometimes those
of other groups as well. This gives you greater flexibility if you want to
switch between funds - for example, if the performance of your first choice
is not what you expected. Of course, with a self-select Pep you can include
whatever trusts you like, within the legal limits.
The first two months of this year have seen a rash of new investment trust
launches. Many of them are not fully Pep-qualifying, as they invest in such
areas as Latin America, Israel and Taiwan, but a number are aimed squarely
at the Pep market.
Buying investment trust shares during the launch period has its attractions,
particularly when other trusts in the same sector are trading at large
premiums. Buyers of new issues pay only the net asset value, plus the issue
expenses, which rarely exceed 4 per cent.
New trusts often aim to compensate for the dent made by issue expenses by
attaching warrants to the new shares. Warrants give investors the right to
purchase shares in the future at a fixed price. They can be traded
separately, and acquire a value because investors expect the market price of
the shares to rise above the warrants' exercise price by the time they can
be used. Warrants attached to newly-issued shares can sometimes be
transferred into a Pep along with the shares.
Many new investment trust issues offer very attractive terms for investors
who opt for a Pep attached to the trust. However, if you commit your Pep
allowance for this year to a Pep tied to a new issue, you run the risk that
the offer will be over-subscribed, so that applications have to be scaled
down, and you may not be allocated enough shares use up your Pep allowance.
Rather than Pounds 6,000-worth of shares, you could end up with only Pounds
2,000 or so. To take full advantage of your Pep allowance, you would then
have to buy more shares on the open market, probably at a higher price.
Some trusts promise not to scale back small applications, or hold a ballot,
so that Pep applicants are allocated either their full amount or nothing at
all, leaving them free to take out a Pep elsewhere. If you fear a trust
might be over-subscribed, it is worth inquiring what the attitude towards
Pep investors is likely to be.
A potential drawback for keen investors is that buying investment trust
shares via a Pep makes it more difficult to participate in shareholders
meetings. Most Pep managers make an extra charge - commonly Pounds 10-Pounds
25, but it can be as much as Pounds 50 - if you want to attend an AGM. A few
managers, such as Flemings, make a point of not charging for this service.
If shareholder participation is important to you, check this point before
you sign up.
For an information pack on investment trusts, write to: Association of
Investment Trust Companies, Park House (6th Floor), 16 Finsbury Circus,
London EC2M 7JJ.
