<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / FT Guide to Personal Equity Plans - Unit Trusts (4): Check
how they've performed - Once you have made up your mind to invest, the most
important factor is consistency. And there are several publications that
monitor statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unit trusts have had good reason to be grateful to personal equity plans.
Last year, a record Pounds 9.1bn was poured into the industry, with private
investors accounting for Pounds 5bn of this net investment (gross investment
less redemptions). They chose to channel nearly two-thirds of their money
through a personal equity plan, attesting to the sustained popularity of
Peps as a way of investing in equity markets.
Both unit and investment trusts benefited from the decision by former
chancellor Norman Lamont to lift the Pounds 3,000 limit on collective-fund
Pep investment from the 1992 tax year.
Some restrictions still remain. A unit trust must have more than 50 per cent
of the fund invested in Europe to qualify for the full general Pep allowance
of Pounds 6,000. The many unit trusts that do not meet this requirement are
'non-qualifying', and only Pounds 1,500 of the fund can be invested in the
Pep. The remaining Pounds 4,500 of the allowance can be made up with
qualifying trusts, investment trusts or shares.
An investor contemplating a Pep will find that unit trusts have the
advantage over investment trusts, at least in terms of charges, because many
unit trust managers will put the investment into a Pep for no extra cost.
This means that anyone who wants to make a unit trust investment may as well
shelter some of it in a Pep (see article on charges, on page 4).
If your chosen trust does not have a Pep attached to it, you will have to
use a self-select Pep, but there will be additional charges, since most plan
managers will levy an annual fee and are likely to charge for the collection
of dividends.
Moreover, some unit trust companies offer lower initial charges for direct
investment, but the same reduction may not be on offer to private investors
buying through the self-select route. On the other hand, some stockbrokers
are able to obtain discounts on the initial charge of a large number of unit
trusts.
Once you have run through the arguments and decided to invest in a unit,
rather than investment, trust, the main criteria for choosing the Pep will
be the performance of the unit trust company. The most important
characteristic to look out for is consistency of performance. The FT's
sister publication, Money Management magazine, carries performance
statistics every month, and the FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance also
publishes tables ranking the growth of the leading unit trusts over five
years.
These publications divide unit trusts into a large number of different
sectors, categorised mainly by regions but also by income and growth.
Chase de Vere Investments produces performance charts ranking only those
unit trusts with a Pep attached to them. It divides these into those that
are qualifying and non-qualifying. The performance charts are published
every six months, and the most recent copy is available with Chase de Vere's
annual Pep Guide*, which gives details of managers and their charging
structures.
Meanwhile, the tables on this page show the top-performing qualifying and
non-qualifying unit trusts in the three years to January 1. It should be
noted that these are quoted on an offer-to-offer basis, which means that the
initial charges have not been taken into account - the actual returns to
investors will have been lower. The figures also assume reinvestment of
gross income.
The top 10 qualifying trusts are spread across a number of different
sectors, including the specialist smaller companies and those which are
income-oriented. The top-performing non-qualifying trusts are more narrowly
focused, and reflect the impressive growth over the past three years of
emerging markets, particularly in the Far East.
Apart from performance and charges, investors should choose according to
their investment needs. An investor in his late twenties may be happy to use
up part of his Pep allowance in emerging markets, but this may not appeal to
someone in the prime of life who hopes that the Pep will supplement their
pension.
unit trust companies try to make the choice easier by packaging their
products to appeal to specific groups of people, although this does not mean
it is not worth the precaution of taking independent financial advice.
Fidelity, for example, recently launched two new Peps, one for first-time
investors and the other for those specifically saving for retirement. The
Moneybuilder Pep is attached to the company's existing fund of funds unit
trust. Technical changes have been made to the trust, to ensure that it
remains fully-qualifying. Mary Blair, director of product development, says
the product is particularly good for first-time investors, because it acts
like a managed fund and gives exposure to global as well as UK and European
markets.
As a special offer, the 2 per cent initial charge on the Pep is halved until
March 11.
The UK Dividend Growth fund is a new Fidelity unit trust, investing in UK
companies with the ability to grow dividends of between 8-10 per cent a
year. Since the dividends will be reinvested, the idea is that this will
help produce a large lump sum which can be taken tax-free on retirement, or
after 10-15 years. The initial charge on the Retirement Income Builder (the
name of the Pep attached to the fund) is 2 per cent and, in line with all
Fidelity Peps, exit charges also apply. Minimum investment in both new Peps
is Pounds 1,000, or Pounds 50 regular monthly savings.
Some unit trust companies will allow you to split your Pep between its
funds, but it is harder to find any that will let another company's funds be
included. A step was made in this direction earlier this year, when Skandia
Life launched a type of umbrella Pep fund, allowing investors to split their
Pep allowance between different unit trust management groups or to switch
out of one company's fund and into another's, without having to pay a
transfer fee or the full initial charge on the new unit trust. Instead, the
initial charge is between 0.25-0.5 per cent.
The choice is not limitless, but it includes some of the best names. The
Multipep offers 30 funds from 12 providers - Fidelity, Gartmore, James
Capel, Morgan Grenfell, Baring, Schroder, Perpetual, Framlington, Henderson,
Abtrust, Credit Suisse and Jupiter Tyndall Merlin.
Because of the low switching charges, Skandia says that an investor putting
Pounds 6,000 a year into a Pep, and deciding after three years to transfer
to another provider, would usually pay about Pounds 900 for doing so
(assuming a 5 per cent initial charge on a total investment of Pounds
18,000). The cost within the Multipep would be Pounds 63, according to
Skandia.
However, there is a price to pay for this flexibility. The initial charge on
the Multipep is 4.5-5 per cent, which is lower than the standard unit trust
initial charge; but Skandia imposes its own annual fee of 0.5 per cent on
top of the fee charged by the manager, so that the total annual fee will
vary between 1.5 and 2 per cent.
Over time, annual fees have much more of an effect on performance than
initial charges. Moreover there is a dividend-collection charge of Pounds 5
for one payment a year down to Pounds 2 a dividend for 12 payments.
* Pepguide, 12th edition, Chase de Vere Investments, 63 Lincoln's Inn
Fields, London WC2A 3JX: Pounds 9.95 (incl postage &amp; packing).
