<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / FT Guide to Personal Equity Plans - Charges (2): Take care
if you pay little tax - Many people have been happy to invest without
questioning whether they are getting value for money - but extra
admininstration must usually be paid for
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The worth of a personal equity plan lies in being able to shelter capital
gains and income from tax. Attracted by the tax-free label, many people have
been happy to invest without questioning whether they are actually getting
value for money.
You can only invest in a Pep through a plan manager, who will levy charges
for the additional administration involved. The main charges are the initial
one and an annual management fee.
On a unit trust, these charges are typically 5-6 per cent initially and 1.5
per cent annually. Since the dividend yield on the FT-SE A All-Share is only
about 3.3 per cent at the moment, the income from the full Pounds 6,000
invested in a total return unit trust Pep would be Pounds 198 in the first
year. The tax saving to a higher rate taxpayer would be Pounds 79.20 and
Pounds 39.60 to someone in the lower-rate band.
Against this saving have to be set the Pounds 330 initial charge (assuming
this is 5.5 per cent) in addition to a Pounds 90 annual fee. It will
therefore take many years before the income tax saving outweighs the Pounds
420 charge (which excludes VAT), particularly for a lower-rate taxpayer.
James Higgins, of fee-based advisers Chamberlain de Broe, says: 'The point
of effecting a Pep is to save tax - if the charges are more than the tax
saved, then the vehicle is literally a waste of money and for most
basic-rate taxpayers, the average unit trust package is just that.'
Gains made within a Pep are also free of tax, but capital gains tax is one
which few people pay: the Inland Revenue estimates the number for 1993-94 at
only 125,000. This tax benefit will be greatest to those who invest their
whole Pep limit of Pounds 6,000 a tax year in a general Pep (and a further
Pounds 3,000 in a single company Pep) and who hold on to it for as long as
possible. They are then likely to make enough capital gain to use up their
annual allowance, currently of Pounds 5,800.
Deciding to invest in a Pep on the basis of tax savings, therefore, can be a
mistake particularly if you are a lower-rate taxpayer. The situation is
different, however, if you had anyway decided to enter the stock market,
particularly if you intended to do so through a unit trust. This is because.
. .
UNIT TRUST CHARGES:
Most unit trusts do not levy an additional charge for their Pep, so you
might as well make use of the Pep facility if your chosen fund has one
attached to it.
Moreover, many unit trusts companies are competing keenly for Pep business,
leading them to bring in lower charges, a process which began in February
1992 when Murray Johnstone reduced the initial charge on all its unit trusts
to 1 per cent, and to 1.5 per cent for its Peps. Last October, the Pep
charge was brought in line with the unit trusts. However, Murray Johnstone
at the same time raised its annual management fee from 1 per cent to 1.5 per
cent.
Fidelity brought in an American-style innovation when it reduced the initial
charge on all its unit trust Peps to 2 per cent in 1992 but introduced
withdrawal charges instead. Gartmore, Guinness Flight, M&amp;G and Scottish
Equitable have also introduced a similar charging structure.
Since equities are a long-term investment, back-end charges are a better
idea than initial charges. Investors who hold on to the Pep for long enough,
escape the charge altogether. However, all those levying withdrawal charges,
with the exception of Gartmore, do so on the value of the fund, which means
that you would have to pay the charge on any growth your investment had
made. Gartmore levies the exit charge on the initial investment only.
Scottish Equitable is the only one of those listed to impose a flat fee of
Pounds 45 plus VAT, instead of an initial charge, and this fee is being
waived altogether until April 29.
Its annual management charge, however, is higher than those imposed by the
others listed. A good fund manager can compensate for the initial charge
through performance, but in the long run a high annual charge can be more
detrimental to an investor's returns. However, the company gives investors a
1 per cent loyalty bonus on the value held in their Pep on its eighth
anniversary.
There are, in addition, many unit trust companies offering one-off discounts
on their Peps in the run-up to the end of the tax year. Save &amp; Prosper, for
example, is knocking one percentage point off the unit price of its Peps
until April 5, while Prolific is reducing the initial charge from 5.25 per
cent to 3 per cent until June 1, in the hope of picking up Pep investments
across two tax years.
INVESTMENT TRUST CHARGES:
Unlike unit trusts, investment trusts tend to impose an additional charge
for Peps, because plans do cost money to administer, and normal trust fees
are low compared with unit trusts. As a result, lower-rate taxpayers need to
consider whether they might be better off investing in an investment trust
through a conventional savings scheme rather than the Pep.
Price-cutting has also been rife among investment trusts. Finsbury Asset
Management which used to charge 2 per cent initially and 0.5 per cent every
six months, waived these charges at the beginning of the year. There are no
dealing charges either, although there is a transfer charge of Pounds 30.
Anthony Townsend, director, said that the cost of operating the Pep scheme
could be absorbed by the trust; and, because of the increased demand for the
trust, the trust's value also increases.
The table shows a selection of investment trust Peps with lower charges.
Investors should be wary of trusts with low initial charges but high annual
or dealing charges.
The Alliance Trust, which has no initial or annual charges, is
non-qualifying, so only Pounds 1,500 of its shares can be put into the Pep.
However, it allows top-ups at no extra charge from a large number of other
investment trusts and UK equities.
Finally, investors should never base their Pep choice solely on the charges;
performance is far more important in the long run; but if two funds both
have good performance, the one with the lower charges will give the investor
greater returns.
