<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Sagging Dow unable to obtain
uplift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks were mixed yesterday as investors tried to shake off the lingering
effects of Thursday's big sell-off, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
In a break from the recent pattern, the blue chip index was the laggard. By
the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 1.12 at 3,838.78, while
the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 pushed 1.80 ahead to 466.06.
NYSE volume reached 274m shares.
The secondary markets showed some improvement. The American SE composite was
1.87 ahead at 467.45, while the Nasdaq composite gained 4.34 to 783.78 as
technology stocks bounced back.
Investors took advantage of a quiet session to adjust their positions in the
wake of a 51-point drop in the Dow industrials the previous day.
Bargain-hunters turned out early, lifting the bellwether index by 15 points
at the opening. However, the bounce was short-lived, and share prices soon
sagged in listless mid-morning trading.
A firmer trend in the US Treasury market provided little positive
motivation, even though plunging bond prices had contributed to the swoon in
stocks on Thursday.
Bell Atlantic, which triggered Thursday's rout with its decision to scuttle
its proposed merger with Tele-Communications Inc, slipped Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 54 1/8 . But US West was up Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 40 1/2 . The
regional telephone group has a Dollars 2.5m stake in Time Warner's
entertainment division. On the Nasdaq, TCI's A shares, which dropped Dollars
1 7/8 on the news of the merger's collapse, rebounded Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 24, after Mr John Malone, its chairman, succeeded in reassuring
money managers on the company's strategic goals.
Among other technology stocks hit hard the previous session, DSC
Communications tacked on Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 54 1/4 , Antec took back
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 20 1/4 . and Cisco Systems regained Dollars 1 3/8 to
Dollars 73 1/8 . Informix rallied Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 23 3/8 after
Salomon Brothers upgraded the stock to 'buy' from 'hold'. A notable
exception to the positive trend was Sybase, a software developer, which slid
Dollars 3 to Dollars 43 1/8 .
Mexico
Equities ended a volatile session modestly higher as investors took
positions and then profits in quick succession. The 36-share IPC index ended
up 4.06 points or 0.16 per cent to 2,596.39.
A total of 145.6m shares had traded, with advances topping declines 57 to
26.
The index moved between a low of 2,566.43 and a high of 2,611.66 during the
session. It closed the week down 112.83 points or 4.16 per cent.
Canada
Toronto stocks ended the week on a positive note, closing solidly higher in
moderate trading. The TSE-300 composite index was up 35.11 points, or 0.81
per cent, to 4,364.23, for a loss on the week of about 14 points.
Advances edged declines 385 to 365, volume of 58.69m shares was down from
68.92m. Trading value was CDollars 786.4.
</TEXT>
