<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Cautious recovery as UK bonds move
higher - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A steadier trend in domestic bond markets helped stem the setback in UK
equities yesterday and the FT-SE Index managed to recover a fraction of the
ground lost in the dramatic setback of the previous session. The recovery
was fragile, however, and although market strategists sounded more confident
on the outlook for European interest rates, they were resigned to a further
tightening of policy by the US Federal Reserve in the near future.
The bond markets continued to exercise powerful sway over equity trading.
Firmness in short-dated UK gilts reinforced views that domestic interest
rates are unlikely to rise in the near term, and there was a good recovery
in longer dated government bonds which had fallen severely on Thursday.
At the close, the longs were below the day's best levels with net gains of
around  1/4 of a point, while the shorts had gained around  5/8 . Some
traders detected the hand of the Bank of England as a buyer of government
bonds. A rate cut in Belgium had little effect on sentiment in London.
The Footsie traced an erratic path as the stock market kept a close eye on
bonds. Early deals saw the Index down by 24 points as the last of the
overnight seales passed through the market. Shares then turned smartly
higher, only to fade as some continental European markets softened, before
moving up afresh to touch the day's peak of 3,283.3 on the Footsie, a net
gain of more than 15 points when first deals on Wall Street looked
favourable - but for only a few moments.
The final reading put the FT-SE Index at 3,281.2, a gain of 13.7 on the day.
The Mid 250 Index remained easier, shedding a further 3.1 to 3,919.9. Seaq
volume increased to 792.5m shares yesterday from the relatively unimpressive
753.8m recorded during Thursday's heavy fall in the market. Stock Exchange
statistics disclosed that retail, or customer business, on Thursday was
worth Pounds 1.7bn, not by any means a record figure.
Last night also brought the end of a two-pressure week equity trading
account which has seen the London stock market fall by about 2.9 per cent as
it has become increasingly concerned by the signs that the US Federal
Reserve is tightening credit policies. This week has seen the pace quicken
and the Footsie drop by 101.4 points in the wake of testimony to Congress by
Mr Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board.
Analysts of the London equity market remained relatively favourable on the
near-term outlook. Mr Marcus Grubb of Salomon International joined the ranks
of those seeing this week's fall as signalling 'time to buy.'
Among London's investment banks, NatWest Markets described recent events as
'A setback, not a bloodbath,' while SG Warburg commented, 'The froth blows
off.'
There was some weariness both in the market and among traders as dealing
came to a close yesterday. The modest weight of selling in equities left
marketmakers to take the brunt of the rapid fall in share prices.
Coupled with increased activity in the derivatives sectors, this left the
big trading firms struggling to get their dealing books in balance for the
end of the trading account. Although nerves had clearly steadied, London's
nervousness in the face of an uncertain opening in New York underlined the
new, and less confident, mood in the marketplace.
</TEXT>
