<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: Contracting out could mean pensions
burden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN HALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Robert Rice's article 'Strings attached to contracting out' (Business
and the Law, February 22), illustrates the problems contractors face in
market testing exercises in dealing with the Transfer of Undertakings
Regulations.
The latest particular problem is the attorney-general's advice that
contractors must offer comparable pensions to those enjoyed in the public
sector. You state contractors may wish to challenge this view. In fact we
are doing so.
At a consultation meeting with contractors last month, Mr Tony Baldry, the
junior local government minister, agreed to withdraw such advice to local
authorities, pending resolution of the matter, after a unanimous protest
that this advice is wrong in law. For market testing in central government,
however, the advice from the Cabinet Office still stands.
Through the Confederation of British Industry, contractor organisations have
since taken counsel's opinion which confirms that the government's advice is
incorrect. Even if the government adheres to its view, because the
interpretation is quite independent of the Acquired Rights Directive, it
would be free to introduce the necessary legislation to remove any
entitlement.
This issue has now become central to the success of the government's market
testing policy. Actuarial calculations suggest that matching the
index-linked pensions of the public sector would require private sector
employers to make contributions of up to 25 per cent of salary. Such a
burden would force many contractors out of the game altogether, and render
many innovative private sector bids uncompetitive.
If the government wishes to maximise the benefits of its market testing
programme, it must now act swiftly at least to reverse its advice on pension
benefits.
John Hall,
director general,
Business Services Association,
28-34 Eagle Street,
London WC1V 4AN
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
