<DOCNO>FT941-7076</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EB0AFAB5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / Trucks headed off at the pass: The Swiss ban has shocked the
neighbours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'The Gotthard was anciently perhaps the most frequented passage over the
Alps, as it offered the most direct and practicable line of communication
from northern Switzerland and western Germany, to Lombardy, and the
important cities of Milan and Genoa. Not less than 16,000 travellers and
9,000 horses crossed it annually on the average, down to the commencement of
the present century' - Murray's Handbook for Travellers in Switzerland, 1838
The problem is the pollution,' says Mrs Marie-Therese Hogg, a young
housewife and mother of two in Andermatt, a Swiss village in the middle of
the Gotthard pass.
Mrs Hogg was not referring to horses, but to the 2,500 trucks a day that
have replaced earlier forms of transport on the ever popular trans-Alpine
route. While in previous centuries, travellers and their carriages brought
prosperity to the tiny Swiss canton of Uri that bestrides the Gotthard, the
trucks bring only misery.
'My older son has asthma. Our family doctor says the incidence of asthma
here is far higher than normal,' Mrs Hogg says.
Mr Beat Baumann, a mountain guide based in Uri's historic capital of
Altdorf, says that, in the summer, residents are often advised to remain
indoors rather than risk breathing the fumes from the nearby motorway.
In the past month, the 34,000 inhabitants of Uri have risen up against their
oppressor, mounting an effective campaign to convince their fellow Swiss to
support their petition to ban transit lorries from the Alps. Knowing that
their own reputation as rather dour mountain folk would not win much
sympathy for their plight - one exasperated federal minister referred to
them this week as troglodytes - the Uri campaigners emphasised the damage
being done to the Alpine flora and fauna by fumes.
The stratagem worked. Last Sunday, nearly 52 per cent of all Swiss ignored
federal government advice and voted in favour of forcing all transit freight
traffic to shift from the road to the railways from 2004.
The result was an unpleasant shock for the country's neighbours. Officials
of the European Union, who had only two years ago agreed trans-Alpine truck
limits with Switzerland, wondered if it was worth negotiating anything any
more with the recalcitrant Swiss. The EU's powerful trucking lobbies were
apoplectic.
If the EU does stop negotiating with Bern on other issues, anti-EU sentiment
in Switzerland could well harden, forcing an indefinite postponement of
Bern's plan to attempt to join the Union in a few years.
These weighty considerations had little influence in Uri. 'The (trucks) vote
had nothing to do with European politics,' says Mrs Hogg. 'It was about our
future.'
Mr Hansruedi Stadler, Uri's youthful governor, agrees. Sitting in a modest
office at Altdorf looking over a square dominated by a statue of Wilhelm
Tell, he asks rhetorically: 'What could I tell my six-year-old son in 10
years if we had not done everything we could to stop the destruction of our
region?'
Uri is not isolationist, Mr Stadler insists. Unlike some other mountain
regions in Switzerland, it has enjoyed constant contact with the outside
world since the 13th century, when the Gotthard pass was opened. The problem
is that the narrow Reuss valley leading up to the Gotthard is Uri's only
habitable territory. The rest is so steep that only goats and chamois can
survive there.
Until the late 20th century, the stately pace of travel meant that it was
pleasant to be an important transit corridor. Everyone stopped in Uri's
village inns for food and lodging. But since the construction of an
all-weather motorway in the 1970s, it has become easy to drive from one end
of the canton to the other in 45 minutes. 'Most people in transit now stop
in Uri only to go to the toilet, if they stop at all,' Mr Stadler says.
He adds that the fumes from the trucks can hang in the narrow valley for
days if the wind is light and the fog is thick, which it often is. Mrs Hogg
says even the Ursuren valley around Andermatt, high above the Gotthard
tunnels, often becomes polluted because of fumes from the road tunnel
exhaust vents.
Mr Baumann sees other problems on the steep mountain sides. 'Trees have been
killed, then knocked down by the strong fohn (south-west wind) storms,
increasing the incidence of avalanches and landslides.'
Local people also worry about an environmental catastrophe. Trucks are not
allowed to carry dangerous substances along the route, but many do. An
explosion in the Gotthard tunnel would have appalling consequences: a spill
of chemicals into the Reuss could contaminate the entire Rhine valley, Mr
Baumann says.
So are Uri's people satisfied now that they can see the end of the truck
blight? And how do they feel about the constant rise in motor car traffic?
Mr Stadler sighs. 'Yes, cars . . . obviously, we would prefer that more of
them would take the old road and stop at our inns.'
</TEXT>
