<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: Bureaucracy stalls road building
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN STEWART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Long public inquiries are not the main reason for the length of time it
takes to build a road. The average public inquiry lasts just 16 days. The
lengthy public inquiries, such as those at Twyford Down or the M11, are the
exception.
The main reason it takes 13 years to plan and build a road lies somewhere
within the cumbersome bureaucracy of the Department of Transport. Transport
secretary John MacGregor's high-profile campaign ('Faster inquiries aim to
cut years off road building', February 23) to shorten public inquiries will
do little to alter that.
John Stewart,
chairman,
The Alliance Against Road Building,
13 Stockwell Road,
London SW9 9AU
