<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / Labour row over poll candidate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour party workers in Rotherham, South Yorkshire, yesterday accused the
party's national executive committee of betraying the principles of
one-member-one-vote by refusing to consider a popular local candidate to
stand in the town's forthcoming by-election.
Members of Rotherham's constituency Labour party said they were 'up in arms'
over an NEC decision to draw up a short-list of candidates for the
by-election without including Mr Peter Thirlwall. He was recently nominated
as candidate by party members in five of the constituency's eight wards, and
by a majority of local union branches.
In accordance with Labour's rules the preliminary nominations were followed
by interviews with a sub-committee of the NEC, which this week drew up a
short-list on which the party can make its final vote.
The sub-committee, which included Miss Margaret Beckett, the deputy leader,
and Miss Hilary Armstrong, parliamentary private secretary to Mr John Smith,
drew up a list of six candidates that did not include Mr Thirlwall. Among
those chosen were Mr Denis MacShane, a well-known Labour party figure and
veteran trade unionist.
The NEC gave no reason for its decision to exclude Mr Thirlwall, who claims
to belong to the party's mainstream.
Mr Larry Whitty, the party's general secretary, said that each member of the
short-list 'must be able to withstand the pressures which come from the
national attention which will be given to this by-election'. The six
individuals chosen had met the required criteria.
Mr Thirlwall, an engineer with Rotherham Borough Council, said yesterday
that he would easily have won the final ballot had he been nominated, and
that this might have deprived the executive of pushing through a more
favoured candidate.
Ms Georgina Boyes, a member of the executive of the Rotherham constituency
Labour party, said the decision had caused anguish among party members.
She said: 'I think it's important that, having chosen OMOV as the main way
of selecting candidates, the whole process should be considered carefully.
Local wishes must be taken into account. The process is open to abuse.'
Ms Boyes said that a recent meeting of the CLP's executive had voted
overwhelmingly to demand Mr Thirlwall's inclusion in the final short-list.
'Ninety per cent of the executive are up in arms, if not more,' she said.
Mr Whitty said last night that the NEC's decision was final.
</TEXT>
