<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / The Malaysian Trade Ban: Companies fear losing a shop window
 -Impact on Britain / Malaysia's ban on state contracts for British
companies in protest at reports of corruption by the UK media has taken John
Major's government by surprise and doubled its embarrassment over the Pergau
dam affair. FT writers explain the background to the conflict and the depth
of the troubles now facing UK companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Malaysian government's boycott of British goods has caused widespread
alarm among UK companies. The main threat, however, seems largely confined
to three industries: construction, defence and power generation.
For the UK economy as a whole, the sums involved are fairly small. Malaysian
government's imports of British goods total about Pounds 500m (Dollars
742.5m) a year, or less than 0.5 per cent of total UK visible exports.
However, UK companies also undertake several billion pounds worth of
contract work in Malaysia on projects which range from power plants to
airfields. More important, some British companies argue that Malaysia is an
important shop window for their activities in the fast-growing and crucially
important Asia-Pacific market.
Officially, the ban on British goods extends only to government orders, with
the private sector left free to buy as it chooses. However, British
companies with experience of the region are nervous that the private sector
might follow the government's lead.
Construction companies are alarmed at the prospect of being excluded from
one of Britain's biggest Far East construction markets outside Hong Kong.
British contractors are working on projects worth more than Pounds 1bn in
Malaysia. Orders worth several times this amount are in the pipeline. The
largest is the new Pounds 3bn Kuala Lumpur international airport.
Other construction contracts pending include Pounds 500m of rural water
projects (North West Water has already won a Pounds 1.25bn contract
involving the privatisation of the country's waste water system); the Pounds
400m Sultan Salahuddin thermal power station in the south of the country; a
Pounds 160m steelworks at Gunawan: and several hundred million pounds of
road contracts, including some privately financed tolled motorway sections.
Taylor Woodrow has previously advised on the private financing of sections
of the strategic north-south highway. Costain, which has no contracts in
Malaysia, said yesterday that it was bidding for a Dollars 120m section of
the country's east-west highway. It was bidding for other work in the
country worth Dollars 1.3bn including Dollars 500m worth of work on the new
airport.
Both Balfour Beatty and Trafalgar House are involved in the controversial
Pounds 417m Pergau contract which is being built by a consortium of
Trafalgar House and Balfour Beatty from the UK and Kerjayah, a Malaysian
company.
Trafalgar House regards Malaysia as an important base to break into other
south-east Asian markets. It is in the process of establishing a steel
fabrication plant in a joint venture with Edaran Otomobil Nasional to supply
steel for construction to the region.
The next largest construction project under way and involving a British
contractor is the first phase of a privately financed light rail system
linking Kuala Lumpur with surrounding areas. Finance for the first phase,
which will operate under a franchise from the Malay government, has been
raised by Taylor Woodrow, the UK contractor, and AEG Westinghouse of
Germany.
Construction began last year and the project is unlikely to be affected by
the Malaysian government's ruling.
UK companies involved in the Malaysian power market expressed disappointment
at the Kuala Lumpur government's decision, but said they were hopeful the
issue could be resolved.
There was relief, too, that the new policy would not apply to private
Malaysian companies. Independent power plant (IPP) projects are increasingly
important in Malaysia and other Asian markets. In these, the power station
is built, owned and normally operated by private companies.
British Gas pointed out that the deal it signed last year in relation to a
720MW power plant joint venture near Kuala Lumpur was with a private
company, Genting Sanyen Power.
Rolls-Royce, which last year completed a Pounds 70m expansion and rebuild of
the Connaught Bridge power station near Kuala Lumpur, said it had a long and
valued association with Malaysia and was disappointed by the decision not to
entertain new contracts from UK companies. Only this week, Rolls-Royce
clinched a deal to form a 50-50 joint venture with EPE Power, a private
Malaysian company, to meet the growing demand for power transmission
equipment in Malaysia.
John Brown, Trafalgar House's engineering business, has two large contracts
for power stations which it is building for Tenaga Nasional Berhad, the
quasi-state utility. These are apparently unaffected by the government's
decision, but Trafalgar House said a big question mark had been placed over
the possibility of future business.
After winning a Pounds 120m contract last September for a 330MW gas turbine
power station at Pasir Gudang, John Brown made clear it hoped to win further
business in Malaysia, a market well suited to the fast-track, mid-sized
stations in which the UK company specialises.
John Laing, the UK construction group, recently acquired a 5 per cent stake
in YTL Power Generation, which has been contracted to build and operate two
privately financed power stations in Malaysia costing a combined MDollars
3.5bn. Laing has been appointed project manager for building and civil
engineering works of the two gas turbine combined cycle power stations at
Pasir Gudang and Paka.
Last year British consultants worked on Malaysian construction projects
worth Pounds 2.74bn representing 5 per cent of consultants' total overseas
work and generating fees of Pounds 30m, according to the Association of
Consulting Engineers.
Among British defence contractors, British Aerospace yesterday said it was
taking part in newspaper advertisements 'to demonstrate that we are
supportive of Anglo-Malaysian relations and want to build up this
relationship'. BAe said it did not support 'the ill-informed and tendentious
reports in the UK press'.
BAe has won some Pounds 500m-Pounds 600m worth of defence business in
Malaysia, its third biggest defence export market after Saudi Arabia and
Indonesia. Last week, it delivered the first of a batch of 28 Hawk
fighter/trainer aircraft to Malaysia. Under the 1988
government-to-government agreement on defence equipment, for which GEC is
the prime contractor, BAe supplies the Seawolf ship to air missiles
incorporated in two frigates ordered from GEC Yarrow.
Mr Alan Jones, chairman of the Westland helicopter group, said: 'We consider
Malaysia is a good place to do business.' We want to work with Malaysia
because it has high-quality people and the economy is going very well. It is
an attractive place to do business,' he added.
BAA, the privatised UK airports group, has acted as a consultant on the
master-planning of the Sepang international airport.
BAA said: 'We were hoping that there would be future business opportunities
and we felt we were in a good position to bid for future contracts.'
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  British industry reacts: disappointed and the press gets some blame
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
