<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / International Company News: Union Miniere to sell US zinc
operations for Dollars 200m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Savage Resources, which eight months ago was a little-known Australian
exploration company selling at 30 cents a share, is to double in size by
acquiring the US zinc operations of Union Miniere, the Belgian metals group,
for USDollars 200m.
The Australian group is buying Union Zinc, which has five low-cost zinc
mines and a 100,000 tonnes a year smelter employing 650 in Tennessee. The
self-contained business accounts for 25 per cent of US zinc output.
This is the second disposal in a week by UM as part of its 1993 long-term
plan to dispose of non-strategic assets to fund investments in its core
business. Last week it sold its 56 per cent stake in Asturienne, the Belgian
mining group.
UM had been planning to float Union Zinc on the American market but
preferred the Savage offer because 'it could be concluded immediately for a
similar return'.
Savage came to prominence because of its successful litigation against
Western Mining of Australia over the Ernest Henry copper-gold deposit in
Queensland. It then sold 51 per cent of Ernest Henry to MIM, another
Australian resources group, for ADollars 92.5m (USDollars 67m).
Savage shares were suspended before the deal at ADollars 1.55. It will fund
the zinc purchase by a five-for-six renounceable rights issue to existing
shareholders at ADollars 1.25 a share and a placement of 50m shares at
ADollars 1.29. The placing will be made to institutional clients of
Prudential Bache Securities (Australia) and Ord Minnet Securities. Both
issues are fully underwritten.
UM and Savage will enter into a commercial relationship cemented by UM
receiving options to acquire 15m Savage shares (less than 5 per cent of the
increased capital). UM is a major cobalt producer. It will help Savage
market zinc and germanium from the US operations.
</TEXT>
