<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / International Company News: USAir pilots ballot on strike
action in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The labour union representing 390 pilots at a subsidiary of USAir, the US
carrier in which British Airways has a minority stake, yesterday began
balloting members on possible strike action after talks on a new employment
contract reached deadlock.
The subsidiary is Piedmont Airlines, one of three smaller airlines owned by
USAir. These and six independent airlines fly under the USAir Express
banner, operating small turbo-prop aircraft that connect with mainstream
USAir services.
Talks with Piedmont pilots have stumbled over the pilots' requests for
improvements in working conditions that would bring them more closely into
line with those of the larger carriers.
The Air Line Pilots Association argues that pilots at small airlines like
Piedmont accepted inferior conditions in the past because they quickly moved
on to larger airlines, but the contraction of the larger carriers has made
employment at small airlines a long-term career.
USAir and the pilot's union said they hoped a resumption of talks would
prevent a strike. But USAir, which is the most heavily loss-making airline
in the US, will find it difficult to give ground at a time when it is trying
to cut costs and increase productivity in the face of intense competition
from lower-cost rivals.
</TEXT>
